<div class="blog-faq">
<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>What is the most common risk of plastic surgery?</h3>
<p>Infection is one of the most common risks associated with plastic surgery. It can occur at the surgical site and is typically managed with antibiotics and proper wound care. Choosing an experienced surgeon and following pre- and post-operative care instructions significantly reduces the risk of infection.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>Can plastic surgery go wrong even with a good surgeon?</h3>
<p>While a skilled and experienced surgeon dramatically reduces the likelihood of complications, no surgery is entirely risk-free. Individual factors such as genetics, health conditions, and how well post-operative instructions are followed also play a role. However, with a board-certified surgeon like Dr. Manoj K Johar, complications are rare and typically manageable.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>How long does it take to recover from plastic surgery?</h3>
<p>Recovery time varies depending on the type and extent of the procedure. Minor procedures may require only a few days of recovery, while more extensive surgeries like facelifts or body contouring may take two to six weeks for initial recovery and several months for final results to fully appear. Dr. Johar provides a detailed recovery timeline during your consultation.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>Are there risks specific to anesthesia in plastic surgery?</h3>
<p>Yes, anesthesia carries its own set of risks including allergic reactions, nausea, breathing difficulties, and in very rare cases, more serious cardiovascular issues. A pre-anesthetic evaluation helps identify patients at higher risk, and modern anesthesia techniques have made these complications extremely rare when administered by qualified anesthesiologists.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>Does smoking increase plastic surgery risks?</h3>
<p>Yes, smoking significantly increases the risk of complications including poor wound healing, infection, skin necrosis, and scarring. Nicotine constricts blood vessels and reduces oxygen flow to tissues, which impairs the body's natural healing process. Surgeons typically recommend quitting smoking at least four to six weeks before and after surgery.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>What should I do if I notice signs of infection after surgery?</h3>
<p>If you notice increasing redness, swelling, warmth, pain, or discharge at your surgical site, contact your surgeon immediately. Early treatment of infection with antibiotics can prevent it from becoming serious. Do not attempt to treat an infection on your own, as prompt professional evaluation is essential.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>How can I choose a safe plastic surgery facility?</h3>
<p>Look for facilities that are accredited by recognized national organizations, have trained and certified staff, proper emergency equipment, and strict infection control protocols. Ask your surgeon about the facility's accreditation, safety record, and emergency protocols during your consultation. A reputable surgeon will be happy to provide this information.</p>
</div>
</div>

